

In [[medicine]], '''Breslow's depth''' was used as a [[prognosis|prognostic factor]] in [[melanoma]] of the [[skin]]. It is a description of how deeply tumor cells have invaded. Currently, the standard Breslow's depth has been replaced by the AJCC depth. Originally, Breslow's depth was divided into 5 stages.<ref name=pmid5477666>{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/00000658-197011000-00017 |title=Thickness, Cross-Sectional Areas and Depth of Invasion in the Prognosis of Cutaneous Melanoma |year=1970 |last1=Breslow |first1=Alexander |journal=Annals of Surgery |volume=172 |issue=5 |pages=902–8 |pmid=5477666 |pmc=1397358}}</ref>
