==Clark's level==

Clark's level is a related [[Staging (pathology)|staging system]], used in conjunction with Breslow's depth, which describes the level of anatomical invasion of the melanoma in the skin.<ref name = weedon>Weedon, D. '''Skin pathology'''. 2nd Edition. 2002. Sydney: Churchill-Livingstone. ISBN 0-443-07069-5{{Page needed|date=February 2012}}</ref>  Clark's level was the primary factor in earlier AJCC staging schemae for melanoma. {{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} However, with further study, it has been shown that Clark's level has a lower predictive value, is less reproducible, and is more operator-dependent as compared with Breslow's depth. {{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Thus, in the current (2010) AJCC staging system, Clark's level has prognostic significance only in patients with very thin (Breslow depth <1&nbsp;mm) melanomas.<ref name=pmid11504744>{{cite journal |pmid=11504744 |year=2001 |last1=Balch |first1=CM |last2=Soong |first2=SJ |last3=Gershenwald |first3=JE |last4=Thompson |first4=JF |last5=Reintgen |first5=DS |last6=Cascinelli |first6=N |last7=Urist |first7=M |last8=McMasters |first8=KM |last9=Ross |first9=MI |title=Prognostic factors analysis of 17,600 melanoma patients: Validation of the American Joint Committee on Cancer melanoma staging system |volume=19 |issue=16 |pages=3622–34 |journal=Journal of clinical oncology}}</ref>  

Five anatomical levels are recognized, and higher levels have worsening prognostic implications.  These levels are:

* Level 1 : Melanoma confined to the [[Epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] (melanoma in situ)
* Level 2 : Invasion into the [[papillary dermis]]
*Level 3 : Invasion to the junction of the [[Papillary dermis|papillary]] and [[reticular dermis]] 
*Level 4 : Invasion into the [[reticular dermis]]
*Level 5 : Invasion into the subcutaneous fat <ref name = weedon/>

